Bayesian Inference phylogenetic analysis including all previously detected mtDNA control region haplotypes for extant and extinct Galapagos tortoises (n = 123 ), the museum specimens sequenced here (n = 3 ), and outgroup taxa (n = 3 ) revealed that the Santa Cruz Island lineages are paraphyletic (arithmetic mean: ln L = -3903.81) (
A), as reported previously [ 11 , 15 , 16 ]. All of the museum specimens sequenced here, including the C . porteriholotype , cluster within the mtDNA lineage of Cerro Fatal with high node support (posterior probability = 0.99;
A). The lineage from Cerro Fatal is sister to the species from San Cristóbal Island ( C . chathamensis ), and both are included in a clade with species from the islands of Pinta ( C . abingdoni ), Española ( C . hoodensis ), and Santa Fe (undescribed). In contrast, the lineage from Reserva ( C . porteri ) falls within a clade with species from Isabela ( C . becki ), Floreana ( C . elephantopus ), Fernandina ( C . phantastica ), and Pinzón ( C . ephippium ) Islands.

