Genetic characters. This species can be distinguished from all other Galapagos tortoise species by allele frequency differences at 12 microsatellite loci, which allow assignment of Cerro Fatal tortoises to their own genetically distinct cluster. This cluster is as genetically divergent from the other named species as the genetic clusters grouping them. Furthermore, a set of polymorphisms in the mitochondrial control region sequence (haplotypes) is unique to the Cerro Fatal taxon (
). In particular, all individuals from Cerro Fatal share a set of nucleotides that separates them from the C . porteri (Reserva)
species on the same island and from C . chathamensis (San Cristóbal), the sister taxon to the Cerro Fatal tortoises.
